The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Tuesday, April 13, 2004 				 Hero Honda to kickstart new unit soon
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 				 	 Chairman Brijmohan Lal Munjal (second from left) with managing director Pawan Kant Munjal (third from left) and other officials in New Delhi on Monday. Picture by Jagdish Yadav																								New Delhi, April 12: Hero Honda Motors, the countrys largest motorcycle maker, will soon invest Rs 200 crore to set up a manufacturing facility.																								The plant, with a capacity of three lakh units a year, will be the companys third. Hero Honda has two units in Daruhera and Manesar, both in Haryana.																								We will pump in Rs 200 crore to establish our third plant. Initially, we will hire a workforce of 600, chairman Brijmohan Lal Munjal said. 																								Managing director Pawan Kant Munjal said four states  Tamil Nadu, Karnataka, Rajasthan and Maharashtra  have been short-listed for the purpose but the company is yet to take a decision on the location for the plant.																								We need to do work on the feasibility study, he said. Once the elections are through and the government is in place, we will go back and hold talks with these states, Munjal added. He refused to specify whether the facility would produce scooters or motorcycles or both.																								Hero Honda, in which the Munjals Hero group and Japans Honda each hold 26 per cent will produce scooters from this year, according to an earlier agreement.																								Hero Honda, along with Hondas other Indian subsidiaries, would continue to work together and target a 50 per cent of the market share, said Munjal.																								The company today reported a 42 per cent jump in net profit at Rs 211 crore during the fourth quarter ended March 31, up from Rs 149 crore a year ago.																								Net sales jumped 38 per cent to Rs 1,680 crore from Rs 1,215 crore a year ago. Other income, mainly returns from investments, jumped 35 per cent to Rs 44,220 crore. The company also reported a 50 per cent jump in sales to 5,92,718 units during the fourth quarter. 																								Hero Honda has announced a massive 1000 per cent dividend for the year. Of the total dividend, 500 per cent has been paid as interim dividend to investors.																								The companys net profit for the whole of 2003-04 has increased 25.4 per cent to Rs 728.3 crore. 																								Net sales for the year rose 14.3 per cent to Rs 5,832 crore against Rs 5,101 crore in 2002-03. 																								The operating profit margin, a key measure of efficiency, was 17 per cent in the fourth quarter, the same as the preceding quarter and only slightly higher than 16.8 per cent a year earlier. 
